  <div class="c-section">

    <div class="o-container">

      <h2 class="c-title u-vertical-space">Kyoto</h2>
      <!-- /c-title -->


      <div class="s-entry-content u-vertical-space">
        <p><strong>(Travel Time: 45 minutes)</strong></p>
        <p>Formerly the Imperial capital of Japan for more than a thousand years, Kyoto is now home to around 1.5 million people, as well as some of the country’s most iconic shrines, temples and castles. The city deserves more than one day’s visit, but for those starved of time there are definitely a few must-sees:</p>
      </div>
      <!-- /s-entry-content -->


      <div class="s-entry-content u-vertical-space">
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Kinkaku-ji Temple​:</strong> Kyoto’s crown jewel, famed for its ‘floating’ Golden Pavilion. Take a break from sightseeing and indulge in a traditional tea ceremony at Koto which is only a few minutes away by foot.</li>
          <li><strong>Fushimi-Inari-Taisha Shrine​:</strong> Dedicated to Inari, the god of rice and saké, its thousands of bright orange torii gates are popular for photographers, whilst those prepared to ascend its 2km trail will be rewarded with both a number of smaller shrines and stunning panoramic views of Kyoto.</li>
          <li><strong>Ginkaku-ji Temple​:</strong> the “Silver Pavilion” is a favourite amongst nature lovers, with long walks around the grounds offering iconic sights such as the meticulously curated ‘Sea of Silver Sand’ and an expansive moss garden, complete with bridges spanning peaceful ponds, streams and islands.</li>
          <li><strong>Arashiyama Bamboo Grove​:</strong> Seemingly endless stalks of bamboo line the path on the approach to Ōkōchi Sansō villa, forever changing in their appearance as the light flows in from different directions throughout the day.</li>
          <li><strong>Nijo-jo Castle​:</strong> This UNESCO world heritage site was once home to Tokugawa Ieyasu, the first shogun of the Edo Period, whilst outside - its Ninomaru Garden offers a prime example of traditional Japanese landscaping.</li>
          <li><strong>En​:</strong> Kyoto was where the tea ceremony was born so it makes sense for travellers to stop by a traditional tea house for some freshly brewed matcha and traditional sweets. The En teahouse is located in the heart of the Higashiyama district, and is the perfect pitstop to sample the wonderful teas the Kyoto region is famous for.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <!-- /s-entry-content -->


      <div class="u-vertical-space">
        <img src="{{ cdn }}images/torii-gates.jpg" alt="">
      </div>
      <!-- /u-vertical-space -->

    </div>
    <!-- /o-container -->

  </div>
  <!-- /c-section -->


  <div class="c-section">

    <div class="o-container">

      <h2 class="c-title u-vertical-space">Hattori Ryokuchi Park</h2>
      <!-- /c-title -->


      <div class="s-entry-content u-vertical-space">
        <p><strong>(Travel Time: 18 Minutes)</strong></p>
        <p>Sometimes for tourists there’s no better plan to ‘do as the locals do’, and when Osakans want to relax they head to the idyllic Hattori Ryokuchi Park. Boasting extensive bamboo and pine forests, as well as a dozen ponds and sprawling lawns, this hidden oasis is just a short distance from the city and is a favourite spot for picnics, walking and cycling. It also offers a chance to step back in time to the Edo era with its meticulously restored <strong><em>Open Air Museum of Old Japanese Farmhouses​,</em></strong> featuring eleven authentic buildings taken from all around Japan and painstakingly reassembled amidst rising bamboo forests, ancient windmills and an Arboretum boasting close to 1000 species of camellia.</p>
        <p><strong>Best time to visit​:</strong> early April during the height of the cherry-blossom season when the entire park is adorned with spectacular pink and white cherry blossom.</p>
      </div>
      <!-- /s-entry-content -->

    </div>
    <!-- /o-container -->

  </div>
  <!-- /c-section -->


  <div class="c-section">

    <div class="o-container">

      <h2 class="c-title u-vertical-space">Hiroshima and Miyajima</h2>
      <!-- /c-title -->


      <div class="c-columns u-vertical-space">
        <div class="c-columns__list">
          <div class="c-columns__item">

            <div class="s-entry-content">
              <p><strong>(Travel Time: 80 minutes)</strong></p>
              <p>There is perhaps no more solemn or affecting place in all of Japan than Hiroshima’s Peace Memorial Park. Built upon the site of the first atomic bomb detonation, it features numerous monuments dedicated to those who lost their lives, including the Hiroshima Peace Memorial Museum, the Memorial Cenotaph and the Statue of the A-Bomb Children, however none are more memorable or haunting than the Genbaku Dome (A-Bomb Dome): one of the few remaining buildings from the pre-war period and a sober reminder of the events of Aug 6, 1945.</p>
            </div>
            <!-- /s-entry-content -->

          </div>
          <div class="c-columns__item c-columns__item--center c-columns__item--third">

            <img src="{{ cdn }}images/hiroshima.png" alt="">

          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <!-- /c-columns -->


      <div class="c-columns u-vertical-space">
        <div class="c-columns__list">
          <div class="c-columns__item">

            <div class="s-entry-content">
              <p>Just a brief ferry ride away is the picturesque island of Miyajima, featuring the famous <strong><em>Itsukushima Shrine​</em></strong> - the only one in the world to feature a torii-gate and shrine building in the middle of the sea, as well offering a perfect location from which to enjoy the region’s magnificent sunsets before heading back to Osaka.</p>
            </div>
            <!-- /s-entry-content -->

          </div>
          <div class="c-columns__item c-columns__item--center c-columns__item--third">

            <img src="{{ cdn }}images/miyajima.png" alt="">

          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <!-- /c-columns -->

    </div>
    <!-- /o-container -->

