  <div class="c-section">

    <div class="o-container">

      <h2 class="c-title u-vertical-space">A few other authentic Japanese experiences</h2>
      <!-- /c-title -->


      <div class="c-carousel u-vertical-space js-carousel">
        <div class="c-carousel__item">
          <div class="c-carousel__cover">
            <img class="c-carousel__image" src="{{ cdn }}images/dohyo-iri-ritual.jpg" alt="">
          </div>
          <div class="c-carousel__caption">
            <div class="s-entry-content c-carousel__entry-content">
              <h3>Sumo Spring Basho</h3>
              <p>​(March 11 to March 25, Osaka Prefectural Gymnasium)</p>
              <p>There are only ever six Grand Tournaments of Sumo every year in Japan, and one of those is held right in the heart of Osaka, just 4 minutes’ walk from Namba Station. The Spring Basho tournament spans 15 full days, with lower-ranked wrestlers appearing from 9am in the morning and the superstars taking their positions from 4pm onwards.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="c-carousel__item">
          <div class="c-carousel__cover">
            <img class="c-carousel__image" src="{{ cdn }}images/bunraku.jpg" alt="">
          </div>
          <div class="c-carousel__caption">
            <div class="s-entry-content c-carousel__entry-content">
              <h3>National Bunraku (doll) Theatre</h3>
              <p>For the tradition hunters, Osaka offers a rare gem in that it’s also the birthplace of Bunraku: the centuries-old art of Japanese puppet theatre. Backed by both a musical accompaniment and a chanted narrative, Bunraku generally covers romantic tales or historical revenge epics, and there’s even a giant version of a Bunraku doll - the Kuidaore Taro (a drummer dressed like a clown) - adorning Dotonbori as a tribute to the city’s theatrical heritage.</p>
              <h3>Fast facts</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>1.2m: the average span of a Bunraku puppet.</li>
                <li>3: the number of puppeteers it takes to control one Bunraku doll.</li>
                <li>30 years: amount of practice required to become a main puppeteer.</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="c-carousel__item">
          <div class="c-carousel__cover">
            <img class="c-carousel__image" src="{{ cdn }}images/kabuki-theatre.jpg" alt="">
          </div>
          <div class="c-carousel__caption">
            <div class="s-entry-content c-carousel__entry-content">
              <h3>Kabuki in the Shochikizu Theatre</h3>
              <p>Even more famous than Bunraku is of course Japan’s Kabuki, and what better way to take in some unique Japanese culture than with a Dotonbori craft beer served from a brewery located within Osaka’s only Kabuki theatre house. Shochikizu Theatre is a favourite with locals, who’ll often be seen attending in finely-detailed, traditional kimonos just like those worn by the performers on stage.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="c-carousel__item">
          <div class="c-carousel__cover">
            <img class="c-carousel__image" src="{{ cdn }}images/geisha-and-maiko-performance.jpg" alt="">
          </div>
          <div class="c-carousel__caption">
            <div class="s-entry-content c-carousel__entry-content">
              <h3>Stop by a Traditional <em>​Geiko​</em> Performance</h3>
              <p>Kyoto is known as the heart of Japan’s geisha world. In Kyoto, however, geishas who have completed the five years of training are properly called geiko. Travellers can enjoy a private evening with a Geiko and a Jikata (a shamisen player) starting from around $1200. For those who are after the cultural experience without the pricetag head to a Kyoto cuisine and Maiko evening which is offered by Gion Hatanaka ryokan. During these wonderful events, diners enjoy a delicious meal and are entertained by several geisha who perform traditional kyomai dancing and play drinking games with guests.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <!-- /c-carousel -->

